vectorData.altText: 20. Match the remaining openings in the pterygopalatine fossa with the space to which it leads.

That's right!  The matches are: pterygomaxillary fissure –  infratemporal fossa; inferior orbital fissure – orbit (duh); sphenopalatine foramen – nasal cavity; pterygoid canal - cranial cavity; greater and lesser palatine canals – oral cavity.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
The Pterygopalatine Fossa is a Junction Box

Recall from Lab 4: the infratemporal fossa leads, via the pterygomaxillary fissure, into the pterygopalatine fossa (A). Use the skull provided, with pipe cleaners passed through various foramina, to confirm that the pterygopalatine fossa communicates:
ANTERIORLY with the orbit though the inferior orbital fissure (B), 
MEDIALLY with the nose through the sphenopalatine foramen (C), 
INFERIORLY with the oral cavity through the greater and lesser palatine canals (D), and POSTERIORLY with the cranial cavity through the foramen rotundum (E) and the pterygoid canal (F).

Recall from Lab 4: the maxillary artery enters the pterygopalatine fossa from the infratemporal fossa. There it gives rise to the sphenopalatine artery, which passes, via the sphenopalatine foramen (C) into the nasal cavity.
The maxillary branch of the trigeminal nerve, V2, enters the pterygopalatine fossa from the cranial cavity through the foramen rotundum (E). Here it gives rise to many branches, including those which pass through the sphenopalatine foramen into the nasal cavity.
That’s how these nerves and arteries get to the nasal cavity!
